<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="64" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[169,1383,276,1618]" pageId="6" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[173,284,1152,1177]" pageId="6" pageNumber="64">Habitat.</emphasis>
[.owland pristine forests, deciduous forests, coniferous forests, bamboo forests, and subtropical mixed forests (foothills of Himalayas) at elevations of 100-2100 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[173,1143,1223,1256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="64" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="6.[169,1383,276,1618]" box="[173,1143,1223,1256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[173,435,1223,1256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="64">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
Ratanaworabhan’s Tailless Fruit Bat is a frugivore.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="64" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="6.[169,1383,276,1618]" pageId="6" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[173,308,1262,1295]" pageId="6" pageNumber="64">Breeding.</emphasis>
A subadult Ratanaworabhan’s Tailless Fruit Bat was found in March in 
<collectingCountry name="Vietnam" pageId="6" pageNumber="64">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
, implying births in January-February.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
